          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>The construction of <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/frct-001Z.xml" title="the opposite of an uncloven fibration" addr="frct-001Z" type="local">fibered opposite categories</fr:link> does appear quite involved, but it can be seen to be inevitable from the perspective of the <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/frct-0005.xml" title="fiber categories and vertical maps" addr="frct-0005" type="local">fiber categories</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E^{\mathsf {op}}_{x}]]></fr:tex>. Indeed, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u,v\in  E^{\mathsf {op}}_{x}]]></fr:tex> and fix a <html:em>vertical</html:em> map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h : u \to  v\in  E^{\mathsf {op}}_{x}]]></fr:tex>; by unfolding definitions, we see that the vertical map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h : u \to  v]]></fr:tex> is uniquely determined by a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v\to  u\in  E_{x}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
